body:
if i'm understanding correctly, you're not using int8 for the purposes of accelerating inferencing (i.e. with Tensor cores)
which model is this? why does the model have uint8 inputs if it casts to fp32 immediately?

"if i'm understanding correctly, you're not using int8 for the purposes of accelerating inferencing (i.e. with Tensor cores)"
correct
"which model is this?"
A SSD architecture
"why does the model have uint8 inputs if it casts to fp32 immediately?"
images are received from sensors in int8 just standard 8bit RBG or grayscale images
casting/converting on GPU is mutch cheaper than preprocessing and than sending it to GPU. Furthermore the datastructures are blown up x3 without any information gain. 

Beeing able to process the data in the same format as it is received improves the thruput.

Furthermore this is possible with the CUDA and CPU providers. For many operations (e.g. PAD, RESIZE) onnx-runtime/onnx-trt is able to fallback to another provider when the operation is supported but not with the given parameters, hence my understanding is that this could be done the same way for casts.

I tried to make the point with the measurements above:
0.01ms on CUDA
~1ms on CPU

so a speedup of ~100 for this operation, without taking the more compact representation into account.

thanks for the context and details. yes, it should be possible to fallback instead of fail.
we rely on onnx-tensorrt parser to tell us what TensorRT supports so it must not be handling this case/type properly.

> thanks for the context and details. yes, it should be possible to fallback instead of fail.
> we rely on onnx-tensorrt parser to tell us what TensorRT supports so it must not be handling this case/type properly.

Hi @kevinch-nv , is onnx-tensorrt marking uint8 type as unsupported?

Yes, we should be partition out all subgraphs with unsupported datatypes (including UINT8). 

@joba01 can you share the log of your run? The logging in ORT-TRT is messy so it may be possible that this is not the point of failure.

@kevinch-nv, thanks for the response, here the LOG:

Unsupported ONNX data type: UINT8 (2)

with trace logging enabled, there is no more useful information:
available_providers ['CPUExecutionProvider', 'CUDAExecutionProvider', 'TensorrtExecutionProvider']
2020-12-15 14:13:43.674040082 [I:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:1048 Initialize] Initializing session.
Unsupported ONNX data type: UINT8 (2)
2020-12-15 14:14:20.128606740 [W:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1843 GetCapability] CUDA kernel not found in registries for Op type: Pad node name: Pad__547

When disabling the TRT Provider, the model loads successfully:
2020-12-15 14:16:37.114901169 [I:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:1193 Initialize] Session successfully initialized.

I can provide you the model, with and without the UINT-8 input, on a private communication channel.

This line sticks out to me as the real point of failure:

`2020-12-15 14:14:20.128606740 [W:onnxruntime:Default, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1843 GetCapability] CUDA kernel not found in registries for Op type: Pad node name: Pad__547`

To me it looks like the CUDA execution provider is failing on the fallback due to a missing kernel implementation for this specific pad operator. This may not fail when disabling TRT as the CPU provider may kick in to handle this op. @jywu-msft does my hypothesis make sense?

No this is (not great, but) fine.
When I change the UINT8 to INT32 in the model it can be converted to TRT Engines. The Padding nodes (these are nodes with less than 4 dimensions) are falling back to GPU. But these are not computational expensive and are at the end of the processing.

Because the whole model can also run in CUDA and the second node is a cast to float32 I see no technical reason why this is failing. As you mentioned, I think this is just a matter of partitioning the subgraphs that this first operation stays on the CUDA executor.

@kevinch-nv, sounds like based on @joba01 's description,  the pad nodes are inconsequential. 
should be due to uint8  if converting to int32 makes the model work with TensorRT EP.
